The Board of Public Works, in consultation with the Department of General Services and the Department of Housing and Community Development, shall adopt regulations establishing criteria designed to enhance indoor air quality for the occupants of relocatable classrooms purchased or leased using State or local funds, including specifications that:
Require each unit to include appropriate air barriers to limit infiltration;
Require that each unit be constructed in a manner that provides protection against water damage through the use of proper roofing materials, exterior sheathing, water drainage systems, and flashing;
Require that each unit provide continuous forced ventilation when the unit is occupied;
Require each unit to include a programmable thermostat;
Require each unit to be outfitted with energy efficient lighting and heating and air-conditioning systems; and
Mandate that each unit be constructed with building materials that contain low amounts of volatile organic compounds (VOC).

section.section:
The regulations adopted by the Board of Public Works may contain requirements for:
The development and submission of long range plans;
The submission of annual plans and plans for specific projects;
The submission of other data or information that is relevant to school construction or capital improvement;
The approval of sites, plans, and specifications for the construction of new school buildings or the improvement of existing buildings;
Site improvements;
Competitive bidding;
The hiring of personnel in connection with school construction or capital improvements;
The actual construction of school buildings or their improvements;
The relative roles of different State and local governmental agencies in the planning and construction of school buildings or school capital improvements;
School construction and capital improvements necessary or appropriate for the proper implementation of this section;
At the recommendation of the Interagency Committee, the establishment of priority public school construction programs;
Development of cooperative arrangements that permit the sharing of facilities among two or more school systems;
The selection of architects and engineers by school systems;
The award of contracts by school systems; and
Method of payments made by the State under the Public School Construction Program.

The regulations adopted by the Board of Public Works shall contain provisions:
Establishing a State and local cost-share formula for each county that identifies the factors used in establishing the formulas;
Requiring local education agencies to adopt educational facilities master plans and annual capital improvement programs;
Providing a method for establishing a maximum State construction allocation for each project approved for State funding;
Referencing the policies stated in § 5-7B-07 of the State Finance and Procurement Article;
Requiring local school systems to adopt procedures consistent with the minority business enterprise policies of the State as required under the Code of Maryland Regulations;
Establishing a process for the appeal of decisions by the Interagency Committee to the Board of Public Works;
Requiring local education agencies to adopt, implement, and periodically update comprehensive maintenance plans; and
Authorizing the Board of Public Works to withhold State public school construction funds from a local education agency that fails to comply with the requirements of item (vii) of this paragraph.

With respect to public school construction or public school capital improvements, including sites for school buildings, the authority, responsibilities, powers, and duties of the following are subject to the regulations adopted by the Board of Public Works under this section:
The State Board;
The State Superintendent;
The county governments;
The county boards; and
All other State or local governmental agencies under this article.
